     9‚ÜíClaude Studio is a VS Code/Positron extension that integrates [Claude Code](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code) directly into your data science workflow. Get intelligent code assistance, data analysis, and documentation features designed for researchers, data scientists, and analysts.
    10‚Üí

    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí### üîê **Flexible Authentication**
    16‚Üí- **Use Your Claude Subscription** (Pro/Max) - No API costs, uses your plan's included usage

    18‚Üí- Automatic authentication detection and setup
    19‚Üí
    20‚Üí### üìä **Data Analysis**
    21‚Üí- **CSV/TSV/JSON Parsing**: Automatic type inference and statistics
    22‚Üí- **Statistical Test Recommendations**: Get appropriate tests (t-test, ANOVA, correlation, chi-square, regression) with R/Python code
    23‚Üí- **Visualization Code Generation**: Publication-ready plots (ggplot2, matplotlib/seaborn) for 6 chart types
    24‚Üí- **Plot Improvements**: Select plotting code, get AI-powered enhancement suggestions
    25‚Üí- **Smart Context**: Right-click data files for instant AI analysis recommendations
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí### üíª **Code Intelligence**
    28‚Üí- **Explain Code**: Detailed explanations with language context
    29‚Üí- **Generate Documentation**: Python docstrings, R Roxygen2, JSDoc
    30‚Üí- **Debug Assistance**: Error analysis with surrounding code context
    31‚Üí- **Language-Aware**: Auto-detects Python, R, JavaScript/TypeScript
    32‚Üí
    33‚Üí### üéØ **Seamless Integration**
    34‚Üí- **Status Bar**: Visual indicator with quick actions
    35‚Üí- **Context Menus**: Right-click on code or data files
    36‚Üí- **Terminal Integration**: Full Claude Code CLI capabilities including MCP servers

name: Release

on:
  push:
    tags:
      - 'v*.*.*'

permissions:
  contents: write

jobs:
  release:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
    - name: Checkout code
      uses: actions/checkout@v4

    - name: Setup Node.js
      uses: actions/setup-node@v4
      with:
        node-version: '20.x'
        cache: 'npm'

    - name: Install dependencies
      run: npm ci

    - name: Compile TypeScript
      run: npm run compile

    - name: Package extension
      run: npm run package

    - name: Get version from tag
      id: get_version
      run: echo "VERSION=${GITHUB_REF#refs/tags/v}" >> $GITHUB_OUTPUT

    - name: Create Release
      uses: softprops/action-gh-release@v1
      with:
        files: claude-studio-${{ steps.get_version.outputs.VERSION }}.vsix
        body: |
          ## üéâ What's New in v${{ steps.get_version.outputs.VERSION }}

          ### Major Features
          - ‚úÖ **Claude Pro/Max Subscription Support** - Use your existing subscription (no API costs!)

          - ‚úÖ **Cost Savings** - Pro/Max users pay $0 additional
          - ‚úÖ **Higher Limits** - 5-20x more usage than API key mode

          ### What's Included
          - Comprehensive Getting Started guide with 6 vignettes
          - Example datasets (clinical, genomics, surveys, metadata)
          - R and Python analysis scripts
          - Complete documentation

          See [CHANGELOG.md](https://github.com/shandley/claude-studio/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md) for detailed changes.

          ---

          ## üì• Installation

          1. Download the `.vsix` file below

          3. Press `Cmd+Shift+P` (Mac) or `Ctrl+Shift+P` (Windows/Linux)

    68‚Üí## üß™ Vignette 1: Analyzing Clinical Trial Data
    69‚Üí
    70‚Üí**Goal**: Analyze patient outcomes by treatment group
    71‚Üí
    72‚Üí### Step 1: Explore the Data
    73‚Üí
    74‚Üí1. Open `examples/data/patient_data.csv` in VS Code/Positron
    75‚Üí2. Right-click on the file ‚Üí **"Claude Studio: Suggest Data Analysis"**
    76‚Üí
    77‚Üí**What happens**: Claude Studio:
    78‚Üí- Parses the CSV file (30 rows √ó 9 columns)
    79‚Üí- Detects column types (age: int, gender: string, blood_pressure_systolic: int, etc.)
    80‚Üí- Calculates summary statistics
    81‚Üí- Sends context to Claude for analysis recommendations
    82‚Üí
    83‚Üí**Claude will suggest**:
    84‚Üí- Exploratory data analysis (EDA) steps
    85‚Üí- Group comparisons by treatment
    86‚Üí- Statistical tests to use
    87‚Üí- Visualization recommendations
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí### Step 2: Get Statistical Test Recommendations
    90‚Üí
    91‚Üí1. Right-click on `patient_data.csv` ‚Üí **"Claude Studio: Recommend Statistical Tests"**
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üí**What Claude recommends**:
    94‚Üí- ‚úÖ **ANOVA** (compare blood pressure across 3 treatment groups)
    95‚Üí- ‚úÖ **Chi-square test** (association between treatment and outcome)
    96‚Üí- ‚úÖ **t-tests** (pairwise comparisons)
    97‚Üí- ‚úÖ **Correlation** (age vs blood pressure)
    98‚Üí
    99‚Üí**Includes**:
   100‚Üí- Test assumptions
   101‚Üí- When to use each test
   102‚Üí- Complete R and Python code examples
   103‚Üí
   104‚Üí### Step 3: Generate Visualizations
   105‚Üí
   106‚Üí1. Right-click on `patient_data.csv` ‚Üí **"Claude Studio: Generate Visualization Code"**
   107‚Üí
   108‚Üí**Claude generates code for**:
   109‚Üí- **Box plot**: Blood pressure by treatment group
   110‚Üí- **Bar chart**: Outcome frequencies by treatment
   111‚Üí- **Scatter plot**: Age vs blood pressure with regression line
   112‚Üí- **Histogram**: Age distribution
   113‚Üí
   114‚Üí**Code quality**:
   115‚Üí- ‚úÖ Publication-ready (300 DPI)
   116‚Üí- ‚úÖ Proper labels and titles
   117‚Üí- ‚úÖ Best practices (themes, colors, annotations)
   118‚Üí- ‚úÖ Both R (ggplot2) and Python (matplotlib/seaborn)
   119‚Üí
   120‚Üí### Step 4: Try It Out
   121‚Üí
   122‚Üí**Copy the R code Claude generates**:
   123‚Üí```r
   124‚Üí# Example: Box plot of blood pressure by treatment
   125‚Üílibrary(ggplot2)
   126‚Üí
   127‚Üídata <- read.csv("examples/data/patient_data.csv")
   128‚Üí
   129‚Üíggplot(data, aes(x = treatment, y = blood_pressure_systolic, fill = treatment)) +
   130‚Üí  geom_boxplot() +
   131‚Üí  theme_minimal() +
   132‚Üí  labs(
   133‚Üí    title = "Systolic Blood Pressure by Treatment Group",
   134‚Üí    x = "Treatment",
   135‚Üí    y = "Systolic BP (mmHg)"
   136‚Üí  ) +
   137‚Üí  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2")
   138‚Üí
   139‚Üíggsave("blood_pressure_boxplot.png", width = 8, height = 6, dpi = 300)
   140‚Üí```
   141‚Üí
   142‚Üí**Expected insights**:
   143‚Üí- DrugA and DrugB show lower blood pressure than Placebo
   144‚Üí- Median systolic BP: DrugA (~130), DrugB (~135), Placebo (~140)
   145‚Üí- Suggests treatment effect worth formal testing
